latestIgtvVideos.title: SUNDOWNER SPICED RUM BROWN BUTTER COOKIES 🍪
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Take your cookie making to the next level with this recipe: ⁣
⁣
Ingredients:⁣
170g butter / 1 1/2 sticks⁣
1 egg⁣
1 teaspoon vanilla extract⁣
2 tablespoons spiced rum*⁣
1/2 cup jaggery ( or brown sugar)⁣
3/4 cup white sugar, keep 1/2 cup for recipe and 1/4 for rolling the dough balls ⁣
1/2 teaspoon baking soda⁣
1/4 teaspoon baking powder⁣
2 cups flour⁣
pinch of salt⁣
⁣
Directions:⁣
Preheat oven to 175C /350F⁣
⁣
Over medium heat, melt butter in a medium sauce pan ( preferably a steel one) . Continue to cook it until it turns a dark golden brown and gives off a nutty aroma, stirring occasionally. Please don’t leave the stove as it can quickly burn. (You could even take it further than I did but I didn’t have any more butter so I kept it safe.) Cool for 10-15 minutes.⁣
⁣
Combine flour, baking soda, baking powder and salt together in a medium bowl. In a second bowl, mix together the cooled butter, egg, vanilla, spiced rum*, jaggery, and 1/2 cup white sugar. Gradually add the flour mixture to the wet ingredients until well combined and a dough forms.⁣
⁣
Roll about 1 tablepoon of dough into ball and coat in white sugar. Place dough balls about 2 inches apart. Bake for 10 to 12 minutes or until the bottoms turn a light golden brown.  Serve with chai! ☕️⁣
⁣
*I used the infusion kit by @otane.in for this recipe. ⁣
⁣
*To make it kid friendly, at this point you can add chocolate chips and have brown butter chocolate chip cookies.

latestIgtvVideos.title: TRAVELING DURING COVID
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
I wanted to do a video for you guys that talked about our experiences of traveling to the US and getting tested here during COVID19 in hopes that it gives you some insight and answers some of the questions you might have. This video is only about traveling outside India and not into India which is a different process. I explain the whole travel and quarantine process in the video but here’s a quick breakdown as well. ⁣
⁣
𝟏.𝗪𝐇𝐎 𝐂𝐀𝐍 𝐓𝐑𝐀𝐕𝐄𝐋⁣
- As of last week: those with US Citizenship, Greencard holders, permanent resident holders, and existing visas longer than 1 month can travel to the US. (I would email the embassy for clarification on who can travel)⁣
𝟐.𝐓𝐑𝐀𝐕𝐄𝐋 𝐃𝐀𝐘 𝐀𝐍𝐃 𝗪𝐇𝐀𝐓 𝐘𝐎𝐔 𝐍𝐄𝐄𝐃 ⁣
- a PPE kit will be given at check-in but you should be carrying your own mask and extra pairs of gloves⁣
- Carry snacks as all flights and airports are not fully functional ⁣
- You have to print and fill out the “Self-Reporting Form” for Indian airports. You need 3 copies per passenger for airport officer, check-in, and immigration. Please keep it ready before going to the airport. ⁣
𝟑. 𝐒𝐄𝐋𝐅- 𝐐𝐔𝐀𝐑𝐀𝐍𝐓𝐈𝐍𝐈𝐍𝐆⁣
- For NJ, self-quarantining means keeping a 6ft distance from others while self-monitoring your health at home and only leaving for essentials. We are still able to leave the house for walks and fresh air as long as we are being safe ( which we are)⁣.
- At home we also wore masks around our parents especially if we were in the same room. 
𝟒.𝐂𝐎𝐕𝐈𝐃 𝐓𝐄𝐒𝐓𝐈𝐍𝐆 ⁣
- In NJ, COVID-19 testing and treatment is available to everyone in New Jersey regardless of their insurance or immigration status. 𝘛𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘮𝘦𝘢𝘯𝘴 𝘪𝘵’𝘴 𝐟𝐫𝐞𝐞 𝘸𝘩𝘦𝘵𝘩𝘦𝘳 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘩𝘢𝘷𝘦 𝘪𝘯𝘴𝘶𝘳𝘢𝘯𝘤𝘦 𝘰𝘳 𝘯𝘰𝘵. ⁣
- I did an at-home test where they send your kit home and you work with a supervisor online and then mail it in for the results. ⁣
 - Benny’s test was done at the local drive-thru pharmacy. It was a self-administered, we stayed in the car while someone supervised. ⁣
- Update: we both got our results and we are COVID- Negative! 🙏🏼⁣
⁣
This was our experience but always read up, things are changing everyday! ☺️

latestIgtvVideos.title: Coq Au Vin ( Chicken in wine) dish I made over 3 days for our anniversary.
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Ingredients: 
3 lbs chicken thighs&legs
2.5 tsp salt/ as needed
1/2 tsp ground pepper
3 cups hearty red wine
1 bay leaf
1 tsp chopped fresh thyme
4 oz Lardon/ bacon
Olive oil ( as needed)
1 large onion, diced (2-3 smaller red onions)
1 large carrot, diced (2 smaller carrots)
8 ounce white/brown mushrooms, sliced
2 garlic cloves (4-5 indian garlic),minced 
1 tsp tomato paste/ 1 tomato diced
1 tbsp flour
2 tbsp brandy
3 tbsp unsalted butter
8 oz peeled pearl onions ( sambar onions)
Sugar
Bread
Chopped Parsley, for serving
-In a large bowl, combine chicken, salt&pepper, wine, thyme & bay leaf. Cover & refrigerate for 2hr/overnight.
-In large Dutch oven/heavy-bottom pan(with lid), cook lardons over medium heat til fat is rendered and golden&crisp. Using a slotted spoon, transfer lardons to a plate, leaving rendered fat in pot.
-Remove chicken from wine, reserving marinade. Pat w/ paper towel until dry. Working in batches, cook chicken (single layer) in lardon fat until well browned, 3-5 min/side. ( If dry, add oil). Transfer browned chicken to plate.
-Add carrots,onions, half the mushrooms & salt to pot and cook down. Stir in garlic & tomato paste- cook for 1 min., then stir in flour & cook for another min. Remove from heat, push vegetables to one side. Add brandy to empty side & ignite a match. ( If uncomfortable, just let it cook down). Once flame dies, add reserved marinade, bring to boil & reduce halfway. Skim any pockets of foam at the top (if any)
-Add chicken & half the lardons. Cover & simmer over low heat for 1 hr, turning halfway. Uncover pot & simmer for additional 15 min. ( *I let it cool & refrigerated overnight).
-*If kept over night, reheat on low heat for 30 min then go to next step. Melt 1 tbsp of butter in skillet over medium heat. Add pearl onions with pinch of sugar & salt. Cover reduce heat to low & cook for 15 min, shaking skillet in between. Uncover, add mushrooms & cook for for 5-8 min on medium heat. Add mixture & remaining lardons to pot.
-In same skillet, add 2tbsp butter until bubbling.Add bread & toast on all sides. Remove from heat & cut into square, sprinkle w/ salt. To serve, dip croutons in wine sauce & sprinkle w/ parsley. ENJOY!

latestIgtvVideos.title: Homemade Baba Ghanoush
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Here’s another recipe for you guys! Made this some time ago and it came out so delicious. I like a baba ghanoush that has a bit more texture but this one still came out smooth and creamy and was quick to make. It’s both healthy/vegan- use it as a dip, spread or have it right out of the bowl! Here’s the recipe! ⁣
⁣
1/2 cup sesame seeds ( or use store bought tahini)⁣
4 eggplants ( small- I find them less bitter) ⁣
Garlic (as per your preference) ⁣
1/2 Lemon - squeezed ⁣
Olive oil⁣
Salt ⁣
Cilantro ⁣
Sumac ( optional for garnish)⁣
⁣
Make tahini. ( you can skip this step if you have store bought) ⁣
Lightly toast sesame seeds in a dry pan over low-medium heat until fragrant. Be careful to not let the seeds burn. This helps to bring out the nuttiness. Let it cool. ⁣
Once cool, toss in a blender and blend til it becomes crumbly. To make it into a smooth paste, add olive oil until it becomes a slightly runny consistency. Keep aside. ⁣
To make Baba Ghanoush: ⁣
Brush eggplant with oil and char them on your stove. You can alternatively bake them but I find the chariness really adds to the flavor. Cook til tender and the skin is collapsing. Let cool. Once cool, remove the black outer skin so you are only left with the flesh. Add to a blender/ food processor along with lemon juice, garlic, 2 tablespoons of tahini, salt, and a handful of cilantro. Blend til desired consistency. Garnish with a drizzle of olive oil, sea salt, sumac and cilantro. Enjoy!

Kadalamma Kalli | കടലമ്മ കള്ളി | Sly Ocean 

A Kerala myth and pastime, Kadalamma Kali means “sly ocean”. When you write this on the beach, as per the myth, you are “teasing” the great Ocean Mother and she will unleash big waves to wipe it off. They say no matter how far up you write this, the ocean will wash it off. My Appo tested this theory to see if it works on beaches in Australia and it washed off within 5 minutes! 

As someone constantly and continuing to learn about her culture, I love this little folklore. If there are other Kerala myths I should know about, let me know below 💚

Did your parents do this with you?

Hummus + Halloumi Sammie. SAVE this recipe for an easy weekday/ weekend meal! #vegrecipesofindia #vegetarianrecipes #sandwiches 

Went to a cafe recently and tried this and it was one of the best sandwiches I had in a while and wanted to create my own. Have to confess, I haven’t cooked in a LONG time. I have been enjoying the spoils of having a cook that sometimes I forget the therapeutic feeling in cooking something for yourself. This was an easy one for me to ease into as I had most of the ingredients in the fridge ready to go! I know you guys have been missing my recipes so hopefully, this is the motivation I need to get back on it. 

Enjoy this one! It’s messy, flavorful, and filling all in one bite! 

Full recipe 

Bread ( I used olive focaccia but any sturdy bread/ sourdough will do the trick) 
Halloumi, sliced
Hummus, homemade or store bought 
Lettuce, cucumber, and tomatoes sliced ( I had a cucumber + tomato salad already in the fridge so used that) 
Avocado 
Cilantro tahini dressing ( also already in my fridge but to make fresh - tahini, lemon, salt, water, cilantro, salt + garlic- blitz that up and you a done. If that is too much effort, you can use mayo or any sauce you have on hand

Directions: 
1. Slice and toast the bread. Keep aside 
2. Cut up your halloumi into slices. You want to coat this. I used a little corn/ rice flour mixed with water, but you can also use breadcrumbs if that is more convenient.
3. Fry til golden and crispy, keep aside 
4. Build your sandwich- layer hummus, veggies, halloumi, avocado, and dressing 
5. Cut up and enjoy! 

Would you try it?
